# Dungeon Door System Research

## Confirmed Attribute Storage

Dungeon door types are packed into two room-attribute bytes.

### Attribute A

`LevelBlockAttrsA` contains:

* bits `0–1`: palette information
* bits `2–4`: south door
* bits `5–7`: north door

### Attribute B

`LevelBlockAttrsB` contains:

* bits `0–1`: palette information
* bits `2–4`: east door
* bits `5–7`: west door

The low two palette bits must be preserved when replacing doorway information.

## Door-Type Values

| Value | Current name         |
| ----: | -------------------- |
| `$00` | Open                 |
| `$01` | Wall                 |
| `$02` | False wall           |
| `$03` | Alternate false wall |
| `$04` | Bombable             |
| `$05` | Key                  |
| `$06` | Alternate key        |
| `$07` | Shutter              |

Some names describe the apparent purpose of the value but still require behavioral verification.

## Confirmed Configuration Test

The following arrangement rendered correctly:

| Side  | Type |
| ----- | ---- |
| North | Open |
| East  | Wall |
| South | Open |
| West  | Wall |

Changing only the north side to a key door also rendered correctly.

This confirms:

1. The two attribute bytes were identified correctly.
2. The north/south and east/west bit positions are correct.
3. Door types can be replaced independently.
4. Palette information can be preserved.
5. Door configuration is independent of the original visible room geometry.

